<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

	PART

<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	I
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	CAUTIONARY STATEMENT FOR PURPOSES OF THE "SAFE HARBOR" PROVISIONS OF THE PRIVATE SECURITIES LITIGATION REFORM ACT OF 1995
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The statements contained in this Annual Report on Form 10-K (&#8220;Form 10-K&#8221;) of Universal Stainless and Alloy Products, Inc. (&#8220;Universal,&#8221; the &#8220;Company,&#8221; &#8220;us,&#8221; &#8220;our,&#8221; or &#8220;we&#8221;), including, but not limited to, the statements contained in Item 1, &#8220;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Business
</FONT>
	,&#8221; and Item 7, &#8220;
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	Management's Discussion and Analysis of the Financial Condition and Results of Operations,
</FONT>
	&#8221; along with statements contained in other reports that we have filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission (the &#8220;SEC&#8221;), external documents and oral presentations, which are not historical facts are considered to be "forward-looking statements" within the meaning of Section 27A of the Securities Act of 1933, as amended, and Section 21E of the Securities Act of 1934, as amended.&nbsp;&nbsp;These statements which may be expressed in a variety of ways, including the use of forward looking terminology such as &#8220;believe,&#8221; &#8220;expect,&#8221; &#8220;seek,&#8221; &#8220;intend,&#8221; &#8220;may,&#8221; &#8220;will,&#8221; &#8220;should,&#8221; &#8220;could,&#8221; &#8220;potential,&#8221; &#8220;continue,&#8221; &#8220;estimate,&#8221; &#8220;plan,&#8221; or &#8220;anticipate,&#8221; or the negatives thereof, other variations thereon or compatible terminology, relate to, among other things, statements regarding future growth, cost savings, expanded production capacity, broader product lines, greater capacity to meet customer quality reliability, price and delivery needs, enhanced competitive posture, and the effect of new accounting pronouncements.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not undertake any obligation to publicly update any forward-looking statements.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<EFX_BUSINESS>
<A NAME="FIS_BUSINESS"></A>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:13.08%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ITEM&#160;1.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<A NAME="USAP-10K_20161231_HTM_ITEM_1_BUSINESS">
</A>
<A NAME="USAP-10K_20161231_HTM_ITEM_1_BUSINESS">
</A>
	BUSINESS
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Universal, which was incorporated in 1994, and its wholly-owned subsidiaries, manufacture and market semi-finished and finished specialty steel products, including stainless steel, nickel alloys, tool steel and certain other premium alloyed steels.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our manufacturing process involves melting, remelting, heat treating, hot and cold rolling, forging, machining and cold drawing of semi-finished and finished specialty steels.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our products are sold to service centers, forgers, rerollers, original equipment manufacturers (&#8220;OEMs&#8221;) and wire redrawers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our customers further process our products for use in a variety of industries, including the aerospace, power generation, oil and gas, heavy equipment and general industrial markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;We also perform conversion services on materials supplied by customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We operate in four locations: Bridgeville and Titusville, Pennsylvania; Dunkirk, New York; and North Jackson, Ohio.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our corporate headquarters is located at our Bridgeville location.&nbsp;&nbsp;We operate these four manufacturing locations as one reportable business segment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We produce a wide variety of specialty steel grades using several manufacturing processes including argon oxygen decarburization (&#8220;AOD&#8221;), electro-slag remelted (&#8220;ESR&#8221;), vacuum induction melting (&#8220;VIM&#8221;) and vacuum-arc remelted (&#8220;VAR&#8221;).&nbsp;&nbsp;At our Bridgeville and North Jackson facilities, we produce specialty steel products in the form of semi-finished and finished long products (ingots, blooms, billets and bars).&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, the Bridgeville facility produces flat rolled products (slabs and plates).&nbsp;&nbsp;Semi-finished long products are primarily used by our Dunkirk facility and certain customers to produce finished bar, rod, wire and plate products.&nbsp;&nbsp;Finished bar products that we manufacture are primarily used by OEMs and by service center customers for distribution to a variety of end users.&nbsp;&nbsp;We also produce customized shapes primarily for OEMs that are cold rolled from purchased coiled strip, flat bar or extruded bar at our precision rolled products department, located at our Titusville facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	INDUSTRY OVERVIEW
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The specialty steel industry is a relatively small but distinct segment of the overall steel industry. Specialty steels include stainless steels, nickel alloys, tool steels, electrical steels, high-temperature alloys, magnetic alloys and electronic alloys.&nbsp;&nbsp;Specialty steels are made with a high alloy content, suitable for use in environments that demand exceptional hardness, toughness, strength and resistance to heat, corrosion or abrasion, or combinations thereof.&nbsp;&nbsp;Specialty steels generally must conform to more demanding customer specifications for consistency, straightness and surface finish than carbon steels.&nbsp;&nbsp;For the years ended December 31, 2016, 2015 and 2014, more than 72% of our net sales were derived from stainless steel products.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	1
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage4"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We primarily manufacture our products within the following product lines and, generally, in response to customer orders:
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Stainless Steel.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Stainless steel, which represents the largest part of the specialty steel market, contains elements such as nickel, chrome and molybdenum that give it the unique qualities of high strength, good wear characteristics, natural attractiveness, ease of maintenance and resistance to corrosion and heat.&nbsp;&nbsp;Stainless steel is used, among other applications, in the aerospace, oil and gas, power generation and automotive industries, as well as in the manufacturing of equipment for food handling, health and medical, chemical processing and pollution control.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	High-Strength Low Alloy Steel.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;High-strength low alloy steel is a relative term that refers to those steels that maintain alloying elements that range in versatility.&nbsp;&nbsp;The alloy element of nickel, chrome and molybdenum in such steels typically exceeds the alloy element of carbon steels but not that of high-temperature alloy steel.&nbsp;&nbsp;High-strength low alloy steels are manufactured for use generally in the aerospace industry.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Tool Steel.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;Tool steels contain elements of nickel, chrome and molybdenum to produce specific hardness characteristics that enable tool steels to form, cut, shape and shear other materials in the manufacturing process.&nbsp;&nbsp;Heating and cooling at precise rates in the heat-treating process bring out these hardness characteristics.&nbsp;&nbsp;Tool steels are utilized in the manufacturing of metals, plastics, paper and aluminum extrusions, pharmaceuticals, electronics and optics.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	High-Temperature Alloy Steel.
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;&nbsp;These steels are designed to meet critical requirements of heat resistance and structural integrity. They generally have very high nickel content relative to other types of specialty steels.&nbsp;&nbsp;High-temperature alloy steels are manufactured for use generally in the aerospace industry.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our net sales by principal product line were as follows:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<EFX_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE>
<A NAME="FIS_UNIDENTIFIED_TABLE_2"></A>

<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" ALIGN="CENTER" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">

<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PT;PADDING-RIGHT:0.75PT;PADDING-TOP:0.75PT;PADDING-BOTTOM:0PT;WIDTH:52.1%; BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID 0.75PT #000000;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	For the years ended December 31,
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PT;PADDING-RIGHT:0.75PT;PADDING-TOP:0.75PT;WIDTH:1.68%; BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID 0.75PT TRANSPARENT;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
</TD>
<TD COLSPAN="3" VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PT;PADDING-RIGHT:0.75PT;PADDING-TOP:0.75PT;PADDING-BOTTOM:0PT;WIDTH:13.26%; BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID 0.75PT #000000;">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PT;PADDING-RIGHT:0.75PT;PADDING-TOP:0.75PT;PADDING-BOTTOM:0PT;WIDTH:1%; BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID 0.75PT #000000;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP;">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:RIGHT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

</TD>
<TD COLSPAN="3" VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PT;PADDING-RIGHT:0.75PT;PADDING-TOP:0.75PT;PADDING-BOTTOM:0PT;WIDTH:13.26%; BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID 0.75PT #000000;">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

<TD COLSPAN="3" VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PT;PADDING-RIGHT:0.75PT;PADDING-TOP:0.75PT;PADDING-BOTTOM:0PT;WIDTH:13.26%; BORDER-BOTTOM:SOLID 0.75PT #000000;">
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	2014

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	RAW MATERIALS
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We depend on the delivery of key raw materials for our day-to-day operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;These key raw materials are carbon and stainless scrap metal and alloys, primarily consisting of nickel, chrome, molybdenum, and copper.&nbsp;&nbsp;Scrap metal is primarily generated by industrial sources and is purchased through a number of scrap brokers and processors.&nbsp;&nbsp;We also recycle scrap metal generated from our own production operations as a source of metal for our melt shops. Alloys are generally purchased from domestic agents and originate in the United States, Australia, Canada, China, Russia, South America and South Africa.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our Bridgeville and North Jackson facilities currently supply semi-finished specialty steel products as starting materials to our other operating facilities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Semi-finished specialty steel starting materials, which we cannot produce at a competitive cost, are purchased from other suppliers.&nbsp;&nbsp;We generally purchase these starting materials from steel strip coil suppliers, extruders, flat rolled producers and service centers. We believe that adequate supplies of starting material will continue to be available.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The cost of raw materials represents approximately 40% of the cost of products sold in 2016 and approximately half of the cost of products sold in 2015 and 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Raw material costs can be impacted by significant price changes.&nbsp;&nbsp;Raw material prices vary based on numerous factors, including quality, and are subject to frequent market fluctuations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Future raw material prices cannot be predicted with any degree of certainty.&nbsp;&nbsp;We do not maintain any fixed-price long-term agreements with any of our raw material suppliers.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	2
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage5"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We maintain a sales price surcharge mechanism on certain of our products to match sales prices to raw mate
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	rial price changes.&nbsp;&nbsp;For certain products, the surcharge is calculated at the time of order entry, based on current raw material prices or prices at the time of shipment.&nbsp;&nbsp;For certain finished products, the surcharge is calculated based on the monthly aver
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	age raw material prices two months prior to the promised ship date.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	CUSTOMERS
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our five largest customers in the aggregate accounted for approximately 42% of our net sales for the years ended December 31, 2016 and 2015, and 46% of our net sales for the year ended December 31, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our largest customer in 2016, Reliance Steel &amp; Aluminum Co., accounted for approximately 20%, 16% and 18% of our net sales for the years ended December 31, 2016, 2015 and 2014, respectively.&nbsp;&nbsp;No other customer accounted for more than 10% of our net sales for the years ended December 31, 2016, 2015 and 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;International sales approximated 9%, 9% and 7% of 2016, 2015 and 2014 total net sales, respectively.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	BACKLOG
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our backlog of orders (excluding surcharges) on hand as of December 31, 2016 was approximately $43.8 million compared to approximately $38.2 million at December 31, 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that this 14.5% increase in our backlog is largely a result of increased demand for our products due to improved business conditions in 2016 and an improved market outlook in 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our backlog may not be indicative of actual sales because certain surcharges are not determinable until the order is shipped to the customer and, therefore, should not be used as a direct measure of future revenue.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, we expect that our actual sales will be higher than the backlog once the actual surcharges are determined.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	COMPETITION
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Competition in our markets is based upon product quality, delivery capability, customer service, customer approval and price. Maintaining high standards of product quality, while responding quickly to customer needs and keeping production costs at competitive levels, is essential to our ability to compete in these markets.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe that there are several companies that manufacture one or more similar specialty steel products that are significant competitors.&nbsp;&nbsp;There are a few smaller producing companies and material converters that are also considered to be competitors of ours.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	High import penetration of specialty steel products, especially stainless and tool steels, also impacts the competitive nature within the United States.&nbsp;&nbsp;Unfair pricing practices by foreign producers have resulted in high import penetration into the U.S. markets in which we participate.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	EMPLOYEE RELATIONS
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We consider the maintenance of good relations with our employees to be important to the successful conduct of our business.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have profit-sharing plans for certain salaried and hourly employees and for all of our employees represented by United Steelworkers (the &#8220;USW&#8221;) and have equity ownership programs for all of our eligible employees, in an effort to forge an alliance between our employees&#8217; interests and those of our stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;At December 31, 2016, 2015 and 2014, we had 645, 634, and 714 employees, respectively, of which 508, 449, and 501, respectively, were USW members.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Collective Bargaining Agreements
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our Bridgeville, Titusville, Dunkirk and North Jackson facilities recognize the USW as the exclusive representative for their hourly employees with respect to the terms and conditions of their employment.&nbsp;&nbsp;On March 4, 2016, the USW was certified as the exclusive bargaining representative for the hourly employees of our North Jackson facility.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company and the USW are currently negotiating the initial collective bargaining agreement for the North Jackson hourly employees.&nbsp;&nbsp;The following collective bargaining agreements are currently in place:
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage6"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe a critical component of our collective bargaining agreements is the inclusion of a profit
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	sharing plan.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Employee Benefit Plans
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We maintain a 401(k) retirement plan for our hourly and salaried employees. Pursuant to the 401(k) plan, participants may elect to make pre-tax and after-tax contributions, subject to certain limitations imposed under the Internal Revenue Code of 1986, as amended.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, we make periodic contributions to the 401(k) plan for the hourly employees employed at the Dunkirk and Titusville facilities, based on service, and at the North Jackson facility, based upon the employee&#8217;s age and wage rate.&nbsp;&nbsp;We make periodic contributions for the salaried employees at all locations, except for North Jackson, based upon their service and their individual contribution to the 401(k) retirement plan.&nbsp;&nbsp;For North Jackson salaried employees, we make periodic contributions based upon the employee&#8217;s age, annual salary, and their individual contributions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We participate in the Steelworkers Pension Trust (the &#8220;Trust&#8221;), a multi-employer defined-benefit pension plan that is open to all hourly and salaried employees associated with the Bridgeville facility.&nbsp;&nbsp;We make periodic contributions to the Trust based on hours worked at a fixed rate for each hourly employee and a fixed monthly contribution on behalf of each salaried employee.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We also provide group life and health insurance plans for our hourly and salary employees.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Employee Stock Purchase Plan
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Under the 1996 Employee Stock Purchase Plan, as amended (the &#8220;Plan&#8221;), the Company is authorized to issue up to 300,000 shares of common stock to its full-time employees, nearly all of whom are eligible to participate.&nbsp;&nbsp;Under the terms of the Plan, employees can choose as of January&#160;1 and July&#160;1 of each year to have up to 10% of their total earnings withheld to purchase up to 100 shares of our common stock each six-month period.&nbsp;&nbsp;The purchase price of the stock is 85% of the lower of its beginning-of-the-period or end-of-the-period market prices.&nbsp;&nbsp;At December 31, 2016, we have issued 195,904 shares of common stock since the Plan&#8217;s inception.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ENVIRONMENTAL
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are subject to federal, state and local environmental laws and regulations (collectively, &#8220;Environmental Laws&#8221;), including those governing discharges of pollutants into the air and water, and the generation, handling and disposal of hazardous and non-hazardous substances.&nbsp;&nbsp;We monitor our compliance with applicable Environmental Laws and, accordingly, believe that we are currently in compliance with all laws and regulations in all material respects.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are subject periodically to environmental compliance reviews by various regulatory offices. We may be liable for the remediation of contamination associated with generation, handling and disposal activities.&nbsp;&nbsp;Environmental costs could be incurred, which may be significant, related to environmental compliance, at any time or from time to time in the future.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	4
</P>

</TD>
<TD VALIGN="BOTTOM" BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" STYLE="PADDING-LEFT:0PT;PADDING-RIGHT:0.75PT;PADDING-TOP:0.75PT;PADDING-BOTTOM:0PT;WIDTH:53.1%;">

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Vice President of Finance, Chief Financial Officer and&#160;Treasurer

</EFX_NAME_AND_TITLE>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Dennis M. Oates has been President and Chief Executive Officer of the Company since 2008. Mr.&#160;Oates was named to the Company&#8217;s Board of Directors in 2007. Mr.&#160;Oates previously served as Senior Vice President of the Specialty Alloys Operations of Carpenter Technology Corporation from 2003 to 2007.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr.&#160;Oates also served as President and Chief Executive Officer of TW Metals, Inc. from 1998 to 2003. In May 2010, the Board of Directors elected Mr.&#160;Oates to the additional position of Chairman.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Larry J. Pollock has been Executive Vice President, Chief Manufacturing Officer since May 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Pollock served as Director of Tube Manufacturing at TimkenSteel prior to joining the Company and General Manager at The Timken Company from 2010 through 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to joining Timken, Mr. Pollock was the General Manager at SPS Technologies/PCC where he was responsible for the aerospace fasteners business unit.&nbsp;&nbsp;From 1987 to 2009, Mr. Pollock held several positions at Pilkington/Nippon Sheet Glass Company.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Christopher M. Zimmer has been Executive Vice President and Chief Commercial Officer since July 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr. Zimmer served as Vice President of Sales and Marketing from 2008 to July 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr.&#160;Zimmer previously served as Vice President of Sales and Marketing for Schmoltz+Bickenbach USA from 1995 to 2008.&nbsp;&nbsp;He held positions of increasing responsibility including inside sales, commercial manager&#8212;stainless bar, general manager&#8212;nickel alloy products, and National Sales Manager.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Paul A. McGrath has been Vice President of Administration of the Company since 2007, General Counsel since 1995 and was appointed Secretary in 1996. Mr.&#160;McGrath served as Vice President of Operations from 2001 to 2006. Previously, he was employed by Westinghouse Electric Corporation for approximately 24 years in various management positions.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Graham McIntosh, Ph.D. has been Vice President and Chief Technology Officer since November 2013.&nbsp;&nbsp;Dr. McIntosh previously served as Director of Global Technology Initiatives for Carpenter Technology Corporation where he joined in 2008.&nbsp;&nbsp;Dr. McIntosh also served as Vice President of Technology and Director of Quality for Firth Rixson Viking from 2001 to 2008, and also held several management and technical positions at Wyman-Gordon Livingston from 1987-2001, where he began his career.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Ross C. Wilkin has been Vice President of Finance, Chief Financial Officer and Treasurer since August 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Mr.&#160;Wilkin previously served as Chief Financial Officer of Dynamics Inc. From 2003 to 2014, Mr. Wilkin held several financial positions at the H.J. Heinz Company, including VP CFO of Heinz Australia and New Zealand, and Divisional Finance Director for Heinz North America.&nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to joining H.J. Heinz, Mr. Wilkin served as Finance Director for the European Access division of Marconi plc.&nbsp;&nbsp;He began his finance career at KPMG in 1992.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	5
</P>

<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	PATENTS AND TRADEMARKS

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We do not consider our business to be materially dependent on patent or trademark protection, and believe we own or maintain effective licenses covering all the intellectual property used in our business.&nbsp;&nbsp;We benefit from our proprietary rights relating to designs, engineering and manufacturing processes and procedures.&nbsp;&nbsp;We seek to protect our proprietary information by use of confidentiality and non-competition agreements with certain employees.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	AVAILABLE INFORMATION

<EFX_RISK_FACTORS>
<A NAME="FIS_RISK_FACTORS"></A>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:13.09%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ITEM&#160;1A.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<A NAME="USAP-10K_20161231_HTM_ITEM_1A_RISK_FACTORS">
</A>
<A NAME="USAP-10K_20161231_HTM_ITEM_1A_RISK_FACTORS">
</A>
	RISK FACTORS
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We wish to caution each reader of this Form 10-K to consider the following factors and other factors discussed herein and in other past reports, including but not limited to prior year Form 10-K and Form 10-Q reports filed with the SEC.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our business and results of operations could be materially affected by any of the following risks.&nbsp;&nbsp;The factors discussed herein are not exhaustive. Therefore, the factors contained herein should be read together with other reports that we file with the SEC from time to time, which may supplement, modify, supersede, or update the factors listed in this document.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	A substantial amount of our sales are derived from a limited number of customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our five largest customers in the aggregate accounted for approximately 42% of our net sales for the years ended December 31, 2016 and 2015, and 46% of our net sales for the year ended December 31, 2014.&nbsp;&nbsp;The accounts receivable balance from these five customers comprised approximately 32% of total accounts receivable at December 31, 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;An adverse change in, or termination of, the relationship with one or more of our customers or market segments could have a material adverse effect on our results of operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our business is very competitive, and increased competition could reduce our sales.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We compete with domestic and foreign producers of specialty steel products.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, many of the finished products sold by our customers are in direct competition with finished products manufactured by foreign sources, which may affect the demand for those customers&#8217; products.&nbsp;&nbsp;Any competitive factors that adversely affect the market for finished products manufactured by us or our customers could indirectly adversely affect the demand for our semi-finished products.&nbsp;&nbsp;Additionally, our products compete with products fashioned from alternative materials such as aluminum, composites and plastics, the production of which includes domestic and foreign enterprises.&nbsp;&nbsp;Competition in our field is intense and is expected to continue to be so in the foreseeable future.&nbsp;&nbsp;The majority of our business is not covered under long term supply contracts.&nbsp;&nbsp;There can be no assurance that we will be able to compete successfully in the future.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	A substantial amount of our sales are derived from the aerospace industry.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Approximately 60% of our sales and 44% of our tons shipped represented products sold to customers in the aerospace market in 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;The aerospace market is historically cyclical due to both external and internal market factors.&nbsp;&nbsp;These factors include general economic conditions, supply chain fluctuations, diminished credit availability, airline profitability, demand for air travel, age of fleets, varying fuel and labor costs, price competition, new technology development and international and domestic political conditions such as military conflict and the threat of terrorism.&nbsp;&nbsp;The length and degree of cyclical fluctuation can be influenced by any one or a combination of these factors and therefore are difficult to predict with certainty.&nbsp;&nbsp;While the aerospace industry is currently experiencing growth, a downturn in the aerospace industry would adversely affect the demand for products and/or the prices at which we are able to sell our products, and our results of operations, business and financial condition could be materially adversely affected.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	6
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage9"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are dependent on the availability and price of
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	raw materials.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We purchase carbon and stainless scrap metal and alloy additives, principally nickel, chrome, molybdenum, manganese and copper, for our melting operation.&nbsp;&nbsp;A substantial portion of the alloy additives is available only from foreign sources, some of which are located in countries that may be subject to unstable political and economic conditions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Those conditions might disrupt supplies or affect the prices of the raw materials.&nbsp;&nbsp;We maintain sales price surcharges on certain of our products to help offset the impact of raw material price fluctuations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We do not maintain long-term fixed-price supply agreements with any of our raw material suppliers.&nbsp;&nbsp;If our supply of raw materials were interrupted, we might not be able to obtain sufficient quantities of raw materials, or obtain sufficient quantities of such materials at satisfactory prices, which, in either case, could adversely affect our results of operations.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, significant volatility in the price of our principal raw materials could adversely affect our financial results and there can be no assurance that the raw material surcharge mechanism employed by us will completely offset immediate changes in our raw material costs.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our business requires substantial amounts of energy.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The manufacturing of specialty steel is an energy-intensive process and requires the ready availability of substantial amounts of electricity and natural gas, for which we negotiate competitive supply agreements.&nbsp;&nbsp;While we believe that our energy agreements allow us to compete effectively within the specialty steel industry, the potential for increased costs exists during periods of high demand or supply disruptions.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have a sales price surcharge to help offset the cost fluctuations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are subject to risks associated with global economic and market factors.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our results of operations are affected directly by the level of business activity of our customers, which in turn is affected by global economic and market factors impacting the industries and markets that we serve.&nbsp;&nbsp;We are susceptible to macroeconomic downturns in the United States and abroad that may affect the general economic climate, our performance and the demand of our customers.&nbsp;&nbsp;We may face significant challenges if conditions in the financial markets deteriorate.&nbsp;&nbsp;There can be no assurance that global economic and market conditions will not adversely impact our results of operations, cash flow or financial position in the future.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our business depends largely on our ability to attract and retain key personnel.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We depend on the continued service, availability and ability to attract skilled personnel, including members of our executive management team, other management positions, and metallurgists, along with maintenance and production positions.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our inability to attract and retain such people may adversely impact our ability to fill existing roles and support growth.&nbsp;&nbsp;Further, the loss of key personnel could adversely affect our ability to perform until suitable replacements can be found.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our business may be harmed by strikes or work stoppages.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	At December 31, 2016, we had 456 employees out of a total of 645 who were covered under collective bargaining agreements expiring at various dates in 2017 to 2020.&nbsp;&nbsp;On March 4, 2016, the USW was certified as the exclusive bargaining representative for the hourly employees of our North Jackson facility.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Company and the Union are currently negotiating the initial collective bargaining agreement for the North Jackson hourly employees.&nbsp;&nbsp;There can be no assurance that we will be successful in timely concluding collective bargaining agreements with the USW to succeed the agreements that expire, in which case, we may experience strikes or work stoppages that may have a material adverse impact on our results of operations.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our business may be harmed by failures on critical manufacturing equipment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our manufacturing processes are dependent upon certain critical pieces of specialty steel making equipment, such as our 50-ton electric-arc furnace and AOD vessel, our ESR, VIM and VAR furnaces, our radial hydraulic forge and our universal rolling mill.&nbsp;&nbsp;In the event a critical piece of equipment should become inoperative as a result of unexpected equipment failure, there can be no assurance that our operations would not be substantially curtailed, which may have a negative effect on our financial results.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	7
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage10"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our business may be harmed if we are unable to meet our debt service requirements or the covenants in our credit agreement or if interest rates increase.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have debt upon which we are required to make scheduled interest and principal payments, and we may incur additional debt in the future.&#160; A significant portion of our debt bears interest at variable rates that may increase in the future.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our ability to satisfy our debt obligations, and our ability to refinance any of our indebtedness in the future if we determine that doing so would be advisable, will depend upon our future operating performance, which will be affected by prevailing economic conditions in the markets that we serve and financial, business and other factors, many of which are beyond our control.&nbsp;&nbsp;If we are unable to generate sufficient cash to service our debt or if interest rates increase, our results of operations and financial condition could be adversely affected.&#160; Our credit agreement, which provides for a $65.0 million senior secured revolving credit facility and a $30.0 million senior secured term loan facility, also requires us to comply with certain covenants.&#160; A failure to comply with the covenants contained in the credit agreement could result in a default, which, if not waived by our lenders, could substantially increase our borrowing costs and result in acceleration of our debt.&#160; As of December 31, 2016, we were in compliance with the covenants in our credit agreement.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We believe that our international sales are associated with various risks.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We conduct business with suppliers and customers in foreign countries which exposes us to risks associated with international business activities.&nbsp;&nbsp;We could be significantly impacted by those risks, which include the potential for volatile economic and labor conditions, political instability, collecting accounts receivable and exchange rate fluctuations (which may affect sales revenue to international customers and the margins on international sales when converted into U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	If we are unable to protect our information technology infrastructure against service interruptions, data corruption, cyber-based attacks or network security beaches, our operations could be disrupted.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We rely on information technology networks and systems to manage and support a variety of business activities, including procurement and supply chain, engineering support, and manufacturing.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our information technology systems, some of which are managed by third-parties, may be susceptible to damage, disruptions or shutdown due to failures during the process of upgrading or replacing software, databases or components thereof, power outages, hardware failures, computer viruses, attacks by computer hackers, telecommunications failures, user errors or catastrophic events.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, security breaches could result in unauthorized disclosures of confidential information.&nbsp;&nbsp;If our information technology systems suffer severe damage, disruption or shutdown and our business continuity plans do not effectively resolve the issues in a timely manner, our manufacturing process could be disrupted resulting in late deliveries or even no deliveries if there is a total shutdown.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:JUSTIFY;MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Changes in tax rules and regulations, or interpretations thereof, may adversely affect our effective tax rates.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:INHERIT;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We are a U.S. based company with customers and suppliers in foreign countries.&nbsp;&nbsp;We import various raw materials used in our production processes and we export goods to our foreign customers.&nbsp;&nbsp;The United States, the European Commission, countries in the EU and other countries where we do business have been considering changes in relevant tax, border tax,&nbsp;&nbsp;accounting and other laws, regulations and interpretations, that may unfavorably impact our effective tax rate or result in other costs to us.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:13.09%;TEXT-INDENT:-13.09%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;;FONT-SIZE:4.5PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	8
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
</EFX_RISK_FACTORS>

<EFX_PROPERTIES>
<A NAME="FIS_PROPERTIES"></A>
<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">
<TR>
<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:13.09%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ITEM&#160;2.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<A NAME="USAP-10K_20161231_HTM_ITEM_2_PROPERTIES">
</A>
<A NAME="USAP-10K_20161231_HTM_ITEM_2_PROPERTIES">
</A>
	PROPERTIES
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We own our Bridgeville, Pennsylvania facility, which consists of approximately 760,000 square feet of floor space and our executive offices on approximately 74 acres.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Bridgeville facility contains melting, remelting, conditioning, rolling, annealing and various other processing equipment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Substantially all products shipped from the Bridgeville facility are processed through its melt shop and universal rolling mill operations. &#160;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We own our North Jackson, Ohio facility, which consists of approximately 257,000 square feet of floor space on approximately 110 acres.&nbsp;&nbsp;The North Jackson facility contains melting, remelting, forging, annealing and various other processing operations. &#160;Our obligations under our credit agreement, which is more fully described under Item&#160;7, &#8220;Management&#8217;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations - Liquidity and Capital Resources,&#8221; are collateralized by a first lien on our real property in North Jackson, Ohio.&nbsp;&nbsp;Also, our obligations under the convertible notes, also more fully described under Item 7, &#8220;Management&#8217;s Discussion and Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations - Liquidity and Capital Resources,&#8221; are collateralized by a second lien on our North Jackson, Ohio real property.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We own our Dunkirk, New York facility, which consists of approximately 680,000 square feet of floor space on approximately 81 acres.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Dunkirk facility processes semi-finished billet and bar stock through one or more of its five rolling mills, a high temperature annealing facility and/or a round or shape bar finishing facility.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We own our Titusville, Pennsylvania facility, which consists of seven buildings on approximately 10 acres, including two principal buildings of approximately 265,000 square feet in total area.&nbsp;&nbsp;The Titusville facility contains five VAR furnaces and various rolling and finishing equipment.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Specialty steel production is a capital-intensive industry.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe that our facilities and equipment are suitable for our present manufacturing needs.&nbsp;&nbsp;We believe, however, that we will continue to require capital from time to time to add new equipment and to repair or replace our existing equipment to remain competitive and to enable us to manufacture quality products and provide delivery and other support service assurances to our customers.
</P>

We believe, based on information presently available, that the likelihood that the ultimate outcome of any such pending matter will have a material adverse effect on our financial condition, or liquidity or a material impact to our results of operations is remote, although the resolution of one or more of these matters may have a material adverse effect on our results of operations for the period in which the resolution occurs.

	At December 31, 2016, a total of 7,508,154 shares of common stock, par value $0.001 per share, were issued and held by approximately 112 holders of record.&nbsp;&nbsp;There were 292,855 shares of the issued common stock held in treasury at December 31, 2016.

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:3PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	PERFORMANCE GRAPH
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The performance graph below compares the cumulative total stockholder return on our common stock with the cumulative total return on the equity securities of the NASDAQ Composite Index and a peer group selected by us.&nbsp;&nbsp;The peer group consists of domestic specialty steel producers: Allegheny Technologies Incorporated; Materion Corporation; Carpenter Technology Corporation; and Haynes International, Inc.&nbsp;&nbsp;The graph assumes an investment of $100 on December&#160;31, 2011 reinvestment of dividends, if any, on the date of dividend payment and the peer group is weighted by each company&#8217;s market capitalization.&nbsp;&nbsp;The performance graph represents past performance and should not be considered to be an indication of future performance.
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	10
</P>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	PREFERRED STOCK
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our Certificate of Incorporation provides that we may, by vote of our Board of Directors, issue up to 1,980,000 shares of preferred stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;The preferred stock may have rights, preferences, privileges and restrictions thereon, including dividend rights, dividend rates, conversion rights, voting rights, terms of redemption, redemption prices, liquidation preferences and the number of shares constituting any series or designation of such series, without further vote or action by the stockholders.&nbsp;&nbsp;The issuance of preferred stock may have the effect of delaying, deferring or preventing a change in control of the Company without further action by the stockholders and may adversely affect the voting and other rights of the holders of common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;The issuance of preferred stock with voting and conversion rights may adversely affect the voting power of the holders of common stock, including the loss of voting control to others.&nbsp;&nbsp;We have no outstanding preferred stock and have no current plans to issue any of the authorized preferred stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	DIVIDENDS
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We have never paid a cash dividend on our common stock.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our credit agreement does not permit the payment of cash dividends on our common stock.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>

	&nbsp;

	11
</P>

<DIV ALIGN="LEFT">
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="0" STYLE="BORDER-COLLAPSE:COLLAPSE; WIDTH:100%;">

<TD VALIGN="TOP" STYLE="WIDTH:13.09%;WHITE-SPACE:NOWRAP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	ITEM&#160;7.
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
<TD VALIGN="TOP">
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;">
<A NAME="USAP-10K_20161231_HTM_ITEM_7_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_ANALYSIS_F">
</A>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<A NAME="USAP-10K_20161231_HTM_ITEM_7_MANAGEMENTS_DISCUSSION_ANALYSIS_F">
</A>
	MANAGEMENT&#8217;S DISCUSSION AND ANALYSIS OF
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
</FONT>
<FONT STYLE="FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	FINANCIAL CONDITION AND RESULTS OF OPERATIONS
</FONT>
</P>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
</DIV>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The following Management Discussion and Analysis (&#8220;MD&amp;A&#8221;) is intended to help the reader understand the consolidated results of operations and financial condition of Universal Stainless &amp; Alloy Products, Inc. and its wholly-owned subsidiaries (collectively, &#8220;we,&#8221; &#8220;us,&#8221; &#8220;our,&#8221; or the &#8220;Company&#8221;).&nbsp;&nbsp;This MD&amp;A should be read in conjunction with our consolidated financial statements and accompanying notes included in this Form 10-K. When reviewing the discussion, you should keep in mind the substantial risks and uncertainties that characterize our business. In particular, we encourage you to review the risk and uncertainties described under Item 1A
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8220;Risk Factors,&#8221;
</FONT>
	of this Form 10-K.&nbsp;&nbsp;These risks and uncertainties could cause actual results to differ materially from those forecasted in forward-looking statements or implied by past results and trends. Forward-looking statements are statements that attempt to project or anticipate future developments in our business; we encourage you to review the discussion of forward-looking statements under
<FONT STYLE="FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;">
	&#8220;Cautionary Statement for Purposes of the &#8220;Safe Harbor&#8221; Provisions of the Private Securities Litigation Reform Act of 1995,&#8221;
</FONT>
	at the beginning of this report.&nbsp;&nbsp;These statements, like all statements in this report, speak only as of the date of this report (unless another date is indicated), and we undertake no obligation to update or revise the statements in light of future developments.&nbsp;&nbsp;Unless otherwise specified, any reference to a &#8220;year&#8221; is to the year ended December 31.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:13PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Business Overview
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:4PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	We manufacture and market semi-finished and finished specialty steel products, including stainless steel, nickel alloys, tool steel and certain other alloyed steels.&#160; Our manufacturing process involves melting, remelting, heat treating, hot and cold rolling, forging, machining and cold drawing of semi-finished and finished specialty steels.&#160; Our products are sold to service centers, forgers, rerollers, original equipment manufacturers and wire redrawers.&#160; Our customers further process our products for use in a variety of industries, including the aerospace, power generation, oil and gas and general industrial markets.&#160; We also perform conversion services on materials supplied by customers.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	In the second half of 2016, we started to see improvements in our end markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;However, for full year 2016, all of our end markets were down, compared with full year 2015, except for heavy equipment.&nbsp;&nbsp;Lower surcharges negatively impacted all of our end markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;Aerospace was down in 2016 due to supply chain destocking, and oil and gas was down due to the low price of oil, resulting in lower rig counts.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our overall net sales were $154.4 million, a decline of $26.2 million, or 14.5%, compared to 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Sales in the first half of 2016 were down 23.6%, compared with the first half of 2015, while sales in the second half of 2016 were down only 1.7%, compared with the second half of 2015, as commodity prices and demand stabilized during 2016. Backlog at the end of 2016, before surcharges, was $43.8 million, an increase of approximately 14.5% compared to a backlog of $38.2 million at the end of 2015. In 2016, we received&nbsp;&nbsp;28 new customer approvals that are critical to our focus on the aerospace, oil &amp; gas and power generation end markets.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, we added five new products in 2016, with an additional 11 new products in the development process at the end of 2016.&nbsp;&nbsp;New product introductions are essential to move to a higher value product mix.&nbsp;&nbsp;We continue to work on gaining other customer approvals to add more products, with a focus on high value nickel alloy products.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-SIZE:9PT;">
	&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	For 2016, our gross margin was 8.8% of net sales, improved from 5.3% of net sales in 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Despite gross margin in the first half of 2016 being negatively impacted by continued misalignment of customer surcharges and melt costs, full year 2016 reflects significant improvement, compared with full year 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;Operational productivity enhancements, combined with improved alignment of customer surcharges and melt cost over the course of 2016, drove the gross margin improvement.&nbsp;&nbsp;The second half of 2015 included charges of $4.7 million due to reduced mill activity, employee severances and non-cash inventory write downs and $0.9 million related to losses incurred from a supplier error.&nbsp;&nbsp; In the fourth quarter of 2016, gross margin was $3.1 million, or 9.1% of sales, compared to a negative gross margin of $0.9 million, or negative 2.8% of sales, in the fourth quarter of 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Selling, general and administrative (&#8220;SG&amp;A&#8221;) expenses decreased by $1.9 million in 2016, compared to 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp; The decrease in SG&amp;A was driven by spending reductions across most categories of SG&amp;A due to lower employee costs, contract negotiations with suppliers, and reduced spending levels.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, in 2015 we incurred $0.5 million for the exit of a non-compete contract and employee severances.&nbsp;&nbsp;These savings in SG&amp;A were partially offset by $0.5 million additional variable compensation expense in 2016 compared to 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="TEXT-ALIGN:CENTER;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-TOP:12PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	13
</P>
<HR STYLE="PAGE-BREAK-AFTER:ALWAYS;WIDTH:100%;">
<A NAME="eolPage16"></A>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
<FONT STYLE="FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Overall, our operating loss in 2016 was $4.0 million, compared to an operating loss of $30.1 million in 2015.&nbsp;&nbsp;The 2015 operating loss included a $20.3 million charge for the impairment of goodwill.
</FONT>
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	During 2016, we generated $8.4 million cash from operating activities, and incurred $4.4 million of capital spending which was partially offset by proceeds of $1.6 million received for asset sales.&nbsp;&nbsp;Financing activities used $5.6 million primarily for net debt payments.&nbsp;&nbsp;Total debt was reduced by $3.6 million as the net payments of debt under our credit facilities and convertible notes was partially offset by $2.0 million of additional debt from capital leases.
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	The overall demand environment is improving as we enter 2017 with service centers, forgers and re-rollers all signaling improved outlooks now that the pressure for our customers to reduce year-end inventories has passed.&nbsp;&nbsp;Despite customer destocking in aerospace and customer deferrals of deliveries into 2017 impacting us negatively in the fourth quarter of 2016, we remain optimistic about near and long-term aerospace end market growth given the multi-year backlog in airplane deliveries and sustained growth in passenger and air freight traffic.&nbsp;&nbsp;In addition, we are optimistic about our other end markets as we expect strong automotive production and see stabilization of the oil and gas end market as we enter 2017.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
</P>
<P STYLE="MARGIN-TOP:9PT;MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;TEXT-INDENT:0%;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;FONT-WEIGHT:NORMAL;FONT-STYLE:NORMAL;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">
	Our operating facilities are integrated, and therefore our chief operating decision maker (&#8220;CODM&#8221;) views the Company as one business unit.&nbsp;&nbsp;Our CODM sets performance goals, assesses performance and makes decisions about resource allocations on a consolidated basis.&nbsp;&nbsp;As a result of these factors, as well as the nature of the financial information available which is reviewed by our CODM, we maintain one reportable segment.
</P>
<EFX_RESULTS_OF_OPERATIONS>

<P STYLE="MARGIN-BOTTOM:0PT;MARGIN-TOP:0PT;MARGIN-LEFT:0PT;;TEXT-INDENT:0PT;;FONT-WEIGHT:BOLD;FONT-STYLE:ITALIC;COLOR:#000000;FONT-FAMILY:TIMES NEW ROMAN;FONT-SIZE:10PT;TEXT-TRANSFORM:NONE;FONT-VARIANT: NORMAL;">

	The majority of our products are sold to service centers rather than the ultimate end market customers. The end market information in this Annual Report is our estimate based upon our knowledge of our customers and the grade of material sold to them, that they will in-turn sell to the ultimate end market customer.
